Your Digest for Tuesday, Mar 26, 2024 09:59 AM

- **Eearly** loss of *vibration and joint position sense*. 
- Dorsal root (i.e **sensory**) *axonal neuropathy*. 
  **Pain and temperature are preserved**. 
- So, loss of JPS and vibration *exacerbates* the *cerebellar ataxia*. 
- Autonomic nervous system involvement -> bladder dysfunction. 
- **reflexes are eventually lost** in most patients. (but can be preserved in *atypical phenotypes*) 
- Also, dysphagia, *dysarthria*.
- Reduced visual acuity and hearing loss can occur. 
- **Cognition is preserved**.
  • Staggering gait in childhood (due to ataxia of all four limbs) is the main symptom. 4
    • Lower limbs are affected before the upper limbs.

Diagnosis:
Clinical and with detection of expansions of the FXN gene.

X-ray changes in rheumatoid arthritis

The presence of leukocytes in the anterior chamber of the eye is characteristic of anterior uveitis.

Radiographic grading of sacroiliac joints.
Grade 1: Suspicious changes, not definitive.
Grade 2: Small localised areas of erosions or sclerosis; normal joint space width.
Grade 3: Definite changes of erosions, sclerosis, narrowing or partial fusion.
Grade 4: Complete fusion
Source
Syndesmophytes and changes of spondylitis in the spine, which are most often detected in more longstanding disease.
A syndesmophyte is a bony growth originating inside a ligament, commonly seen in the ligaments of the spine, specifically the ligaments in the intervertebral joints leading to fusion of vertebrae.

Lumbar spine changes in AS. A) Shiny corners and erosions. B) Early syndesmophytes C) Spinal fusion or ankylosis
